```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
    // Check if number is less than 2 (not prime)
    if (num < 2) return false;
    // Check if number is 2 (prime)
    if (num === 2) return true;
    // Check if number is even (not prime)
    if (num % 2 === 0) return false;
    // Check odd numbers from 3 up to the square root of num
    for (let i = 3; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i += 2) {
        if (num % i === 0) return false;
    }
    return true;
}

function checkForPrimes(numbers) {
    if (numbers.length !== 5) {
        console.log("Error: Please provide an array of 5 numbers.");
        return;
    }
    numbers.forEach(num => {
        if (isPrime(num)) {
            console.log(num);
        }
    });
}

// Example usage:
checkForPrimes([7, 12, 19, 21, 31]); // This should print: 7, 19, 31
```

This script first defines an `isPrime` function that checks if a given number is prime. Then, it defines the `checkForPrimes` function that iterates through the provided array of numbers, using the `isPrime` function to check each number. If a prime number is found, it prints that number to the console. The example usage demonstrates how to call the function with an array of 5 numbers.

To create a fake chatbot interface with a modal that displays a chat history, we'll use HTML and CSS. Since the actual interactivity (opening the modal, dynamically adding messages) would typically involve JavaScript, I'll include simple HTML comments on where you might start adding JavaScript functionality if you wanted to make it dynamic. For simplicity, this example will focus on static HTML and CSS to mimic the look and feel of a chatbot interface within a modal.

### HTML Structure

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Fake Chatbot Modal</title>
<style>
  /* Basic CSS for the modal and chat */
  .modal {
    display: block; /* Change to 'none' to hide the modal */
    position: fixed;
    z-index: 1;
    left: 0;
    top: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    overflow: auto;
    background-color: rgb(0,0,0);
    background-color: rgba(0,0,0,0.4);
  }

  .modal-content {
    background-color: #fefefe;
    margin: 15% auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #888;
    width: 80%;
  }

  .chat-bubble {
    padding: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    border-radius: 5px;
    max-width: 70%;
  }

  .user-message {
    background-color: #e0e0e0;
    text-align: left;
  }

  .bot-message {
    background-color: #3F51B5;
    color: white;
    text-align: right;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<!-- Button to Open the Modal (You could use JavaScript to show the modal instead) -->
<button id="myBtn">Open Chatbot</button>

<!-- The Modal -->
<div id="myModal" class="modal">

  <!-- Modal content -->
  <div class="modal-content">
    <span class="close">&times;</span>
    <div class="chat-history">
      <!-- Human User's Message -->
      <div class="chat-bubble user-message">
        Hi there!
      </div>
      <!-- Chatbot's Message -->
      <div class="chat-bubble bot-message">
        Hello! How can I assist you today?
      </div>
      <!-- Human User's Message -->
      <div class="chat-bubble user-message">
        Can you help me with my account?
      </div>
      <!-- Chatbot's Message -->
      <div class="chat-bubble bot-message">
        Of course, I'd be happy to help with your account. What seems to be the issue?
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>

<!-- JavaScript for the modal (Optional) -->
<script>
  // Get the modal
  var modal = document.getElementById("myModal");

  // Get the button that opens the modal
  var btn = document.getElementById("myBtn");

  // Get the <span> element that closes the modal
  var span = document.getElementsByClassName("close")[0];

  // When the user clicks the button, open the modal
  btn.onclick = function() {
    modal.style.display = "block";
  }

  // When the user clicks on <span> (x), close the modal
  span.onclick = function() {
    modal.style.display = "none";
  }

  // When the user clicks anywhere outside of the modal, close it
  window.onclick = function(event) {
    if (event.target == modal) {
      modal.style.display = "none";
    }
  }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This code snippet creates a basic modal window that appears when the "Open Chatbot" button is clicked. Inside the modal, there's a simple chat history with two messages from the human user and two responses from the chatbot. The CSS styles the chat bubbles to visually distinguish between the user's messages and the bot's messages.

Remember, this example is static and meant for demonstration purposes. To make it dynamic, where messages can be added based on user input, you would need to integrate JavaScript to handle events, update the DOM, and potentially connect to a backend service for more complex interactions. The commented sections in the JavaScript part hint at where you might start integrating such functionality.

In TypeScript, when you know that a value can technically have multiple types but in practice will only have a specific type, you can use type assertions to tell the type system that you are certain of the value's type. Type assertions are a way to override the type system's inferred type and provide a more specific type.

There are two ways to write type assertions in TypeScript:

1. Using the `as` syntax:
```typescript
let value: string | number = "hello";

// Assert that value is actually a string
let strLength: number = (value as string).length;
```

2. Using angle brackets `<>` (which is known as the "angle-bracket" syntax and is inspired by JSX):
```typescript
let value: string | number = "hello";

// Assert that value is actually a string
let strLength: number = (<string>value).length;
```

**Note:** The angle-bracket syntax is not recommended if you're using JSX in your project, as it can conflict with JSX syntax. In such cases, always use the `as` syntax.

Type assertions are used when you have information that the type system does not have, such as knowing that a value has been validated or that a certain code path will always lead to a specific type. However, it's important to use type assertions judiciously, as they effectively bypass the type system's checks. If your assertion is incorrect, you might encounter runtime errors that TypeScript would normally catch.

Here's an example where you might use a type assertion:

```typescript
function getValue(key: string): string | number {
  // Imagine this function gets a value from some data store
  // and the value can be either a string or a number
}

function processData(key: string) {
  const value = getValue(key);

  // Based on your knowledge of the data store, you know that
  // for this specific key, the value will always be a string
  const strValue = value as string; // Assert that value is a string

  // Now you can use string-specific methods without TypeScript complaining
  const strLength = strValue.length;
}
```

In the example above, `getValue` can return either a `string` or a `number`, but within the `processData` function, you might know from external logic or context that for a specific `key`, the value will always be a `string`. The type assertion `value as string` tells TypeScript that you are confident `value` is a `string` in this case.

Remember, type assertions do not change the underlying type of the value or perform any special checks at runtime; they simply tell TypeScript to treat the value as a different type. If your assertion is incorrect, you may encounter runtime errors.

