Timsort is a hybrid stable sorting algorithm, derived from merge sort and insertion sort, designed to perform well on many kinds of real-world data. It was implemented by Tim Peters in 2002 for use in the Python programming language. The algorithm finds subsets of the data that are already ordered, and it uses those subsets to sort the data more efficiently. These subsets are referred to as "runs".

Implementing Timsort in Lean 4 is an advanced task due to the complexity of the algorithm and the relative complexity of writing performant code in a language that is primarily designed for theorem proving. However, for educational purposes, we can create a simplified version that captures the essence of Timsort.

